## Design walkthrough

Here's every deliberate decision, read top-to-bottom:

### 1. Segment class hierarchy — no ambiguous `None` fields

The old version used a single `FieldSegment(start, end, step)` where `None` had *different meanings depending on context* — `start=None` sometimes meant "wildcard", sometimes "use field minimum". That's invisible coupling that forces readers to memorize rules.

The new design uses four concrete subclasses:

| Class | Fields | Represents |
|---|---|---|
| `WildcardSegment` | `min_value, max_value` | `*` |
| `ValueSegment` | `value` | `42` |
| `RangeSegment` | `start, end` | `1-5` |
| `StepSegment` | `start, end, step, is_full_range` | `*/15` or `1-30/5` |

Each carries *only* what it needs. An `isinstance` check tells you exactly what you're dealing with — no None-checking, no "depends on context" footnotes.

### 2. `_parse_field` is the single shared function for all five fields

`_parse_field(raw, meta)` handles every field. The only thing that varies is the `FieldMeta` (name + bounds). This is threaded through every sub-call, so validation errors always name the offending field precisely.

### 3. `_parse_segment` dispatches cleanly on token shape

```
/  in token  →  step
-  in token  →  range
== '*'       →  wildcard
otherwise    →  single value
```

The dispatch order matters: `/` is checked first because `1-5/2` contains both `/` and `-`.

### 4. `CronSchedule.describe()` is just a call to `_build_description`

`describe()` doesn't contain logic — it delegates so the dataclass stays a pure data container. The description logic is broken into one function per semantic unit:

```
_build_description        ← assembles all clauses
  _describe_time          ← "Every 15 minutes" / "At 08:30"
  _describe_day_of_week   ← "on Monday through Friday"
  _describe_day_of_month  ← "on the 1st of every month"
  _describe_month         ← "in January through June"
```

### 5. Description uses `isinstance` instead of raw-string inspection

For day-of-week and month, a `RangeSegment` gets "X through Y" phrasing; a value list gets the Oxford-comma treatment. This works because the parsed structure is preserved — we're not re-parsing the raw string at description time.

### 6. Formatting utilities are plain, named functions

`_ordinal`, `_plural`, `_oxford_join`, `_format_clock_time` — each has one job and a clear name. No lambdas or clever one-liners in the middle of business logic.

